			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2025</a> paper:</span><br><i>Exploratory, Omniscient, and Multiverse Diagnostics in Debuggers for Non-Deterministic Languages</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/DamianFrölich.html">Damian Frölich</a>, <a href="../profile/TommasoPacciani.html">Tommaso Pacciani</a>, <a href="../profile/LThomasvanBinsbergen.html">L. Thomas van Binsbergen</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3732771.3742719">10.1145/3732771.3742719</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagM">T4D: Interpretation</span></a><ul><li> The contribution is debugging support for non-deterministic language runtimes via multiverse state-space exploration.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5c.html"><span class="tagL">T5C: Testing</span></a><ul><li> It generalizes breakpoint-like mechanisms and exploration logics that support systematic debugging/testing of behaviours.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1c.html"><span class="tagL">T1C: Behavioural Semantics</span></a><ul><li> Non-deterministic execution semantics are central, since the debugger explores alternative execution paths and resulting states.
</li></ul></li></ul>
